sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M33355
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
Pseudomonas putida possesses a two-component regulatory system (TCS) which can sense changes in the toluene level of the environment. TodS and TodT proteins control the expression of genes involved in the degradation of toluene, benzene, and ethylbenzene via the toluene dioxygenase pathway. The catabolic genes of the toluene dioxygenase pathway are transcribed from a single promoter termed pTod, located upstream from the todX gene. The TodS/TodT TCS mediate pTod in response to toluene and other aromatic hydrocarbons. Once TodT is activated, it binds to a site on the pTod promoter approximately 107 base pairs upstream from the RNA polymerase-binding site. DNA bending caused by integration host factor (IHF) enables contact between TodT and RNA polymerase, initiating transcription.
This part should be used in conjunction with BBa_M33350, the CDS for TodS downstream of an RBS, and BBa_M33354, the CDS for TodT downstream of an RBS.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Alejandro Virrueta
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The sequence of the Ptod promoter was given in the article referenced below. This identicle sequence was found upstream of the todX gene sequence natural existent in Pseudomonas putida given in http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nuccore/AB042508.1 (todX coordinates: 14325..15686).

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K274002
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Produces a purple pigment (violacein) from L-tyrosine. The operon contains five genes (VioA-E) each with their own ribosome binding sites.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Shuna Gould
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The VioA-E genes were originally from from Chromobacterium voilaceum ATCC 12472 in the pPSX vio+ plasmid. This was kindly provided by John Pemberton; Department of Microbiology and parasitology, University of Queensland, Brisbane, Australia. (Sarovich & Pemberton (2007) Plasmid 57:306-313). The codons were optimised for E. coli by DNA2.0 (Welch, Villalobos, Gustafsson and Minshull (2009) J. R. Soc. Interface)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: We added complementary restriction sites on either side of vioC and vioD (BamHI, BglII, HindIII). This allows them to be seperately removed to produce more colours from the operon.
